  "prompt": "What is the primary disadvantage of using timestamps?",
  "response": "The primary disadvantage of using timestamps is the performance overhead and storage space they consume. Here are some specific details:\n\n1. Storage Overhead:\n- Timestamps require additional disk space to store\n- Each record or entry needs extra bytes to record time information\n- In large databases or systems with high data volume, this can significantly increase storage requirements\n\n2. Performance Impact:\n- Generating and recording timestamps requires computational resources\n- Inserting or updating records with timestamps takes slightly more time\n- Indexing and querying timestamp columns can be slower compared to non-timestamped columns\n\n3. Additional Complexity:\n- Timestamps introduce complexity in data management\n- Synchronizing timestamps across distributed systems can be challenging\n- Different time zones and clock synchronization issues can cause complications\n\n4. Potential Precision Limitations:\n- Timestamps have limited precision depending on the system\n- Some systems might only support millisecond or second-level granularity\n- This can be insufficient for high-precision time tracking\n\n5. Maintenance Overhead:\n- Timestamps require regular maintenance and potential cleanup\n- Old or irrelevant timestamps might need periodic archiving or deletion\n- Time-based data retention policies add administrative complexity\n\nWhile timestamps provide valuable metadata about when events occur, these disadvantages should be carefully considered when implementing them in a system.",
